The '''Initiative on Global Markets''' ('''IGM''') is a research center<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kristaseidl.com/university-of-chicago-booth-school-of-business/ |title=Initiative on Global Markets Annual Report |publisher=Krista Seidl Design, Co. |accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref> at the [[University of Chicago]] [[Booth School of Business]]. The initiative supports original research on [[international business]], [[financial market]]s, and [[public policy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uchicago.edu/research/center/initiative_on_global_markets/ |title=Initiative on Global Markets |publisher=The University of Chicago |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.povertyactionlab.org/partners/university-chicago-booth-school-business-initiative-global-markets |title=University of Chicago Booth School of Business Initiative on Global Markets |publisher=[[Abdul Latif Jameel Poverty Action Lab]] |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> The IGM is most famous for the IGM Forum, which conducts polls on top US economists. The IGM also organizes and sponsors conferences.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chicagobooth.edu/~/media/5D6639BCEEC84C75820639866F0F168D.pdf |accessdate=October 5, 2016 |title=Initiative on Global Markets: 2010â€“11 Year in Review}}</ref>

==History==

The Initiative on Global Markets was launched with a founding grant from the Chicago Mercantile Exchange Trust (CME Trust).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/summary?doi=10.1.1.173.7142 |title=Leveraged Losses: Lessons from the Mortgage Market Meltdown |accessdate=October 5, 2016 |first1=David |last1=Greenlaw |first2=Jan |last2=Hatzius |first3=Anil K. |last3=Kashyap |first4=Hyun Song |last4=Shin |year=2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://philanthropynewsdigest.org/news/chicago-mercantile-exchange-trust-awards-its-first-grants |title=Chicago Mercantile Exchange Trust Awards Its First Grants |publisher=Philanthropy News Digest |accessdate=October 5, 2016 |date=December 14, 2006}}</ref>

==IGM Forum==

===Surveyed economists===

As of July 2016, the IGM Forum panel has 51 economists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.igmchicago.org/igm-economic-experts-panel/participants |title=Participants |publisher=IGM Forum |accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref>

According to economist [[Justin Wolfers]], the economists surveyed by the IGM Forum are geographically and ideologically diverse and are "a good sample of the leading economists in the nation".<ref name=nyt_stimulus />

In November 2013, ten new economists joined the IGM Forum.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.igmchicago.org/uncategorized/10-new-economic-experts-join-the-igm-panel |title=10 New Economic Experts join the IGM Panel |publisher=IGM Forum |accessdate=July 8, 2016 |date=November 6, 2013}}</ref>

===Coverage===

''[[The New York Times]]'' has cited the IGM Forum polls on raising the minimum wage,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/04/what-economists-think-about-raising-the-minimum-wage/ |author=Catherine Rampell |date=March 4, 2013 |title=What Economists Think About Raising the Minimum Wage |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref> the utility to consumers of allowing services such as [[Uber (company)|Uber]] and [[Lyft]] to compete on equal footing with taxi firms,<ref name=nyt_uber /> and the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]].<ref name=nyt_stimulus>{{cite web |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/30/upshot/what-debate-economists-agree-the-stimulus-lifted-the-economy.html |author=Justin Wolfers |date=July 29, 2014 |title=What Debate? Economists Agree the Stimulus Lifted the Economy |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref>

''[[Forbes]]'' has also cited the IGM Forum survey on high-skilled immigration, noting the consensus in favor of immigration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/modeledbehavior/2013/02/12/economists-agree-high-skilled-immigration-makes-americans-better-off/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507111456/http://www.forbes.com/sites/modeledbehavior/2013/02/12/economists-agree-high-skilled-immigration-makes-americans-better-off/ |archivedate=May 7, 2016 |author=Adam Ozimek |date=February 12, 2013 |title=Economists Agree: High-Skilled Immigration Makes Americans Better Off |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref>

''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' has cited the IGM Forum survey on tax cuts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usnews.com/opinion/blogs/economic-intelligence/2012/06/29/economists-agree-tax-cuts-cost-revenue--- |author=Chad Stone |date=June 29, 2012 |title=Economists Agree: Tax Cuts Cost Revenue |publisher=''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' |accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref>

===Reception===

''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the IGM Forum for providing "an easily digested summary of the insights of mainstream economics into continuing political controversies".<ref name=nyt_uber>{{cite web |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/01/upshot/uber-improves-life-economists-agree.html |author=Justin Wolfers |date=September 30, 2014 |title=Uber Improves Life, Economists Agree |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref>

[[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Memorial Prize]] laureate [[Paul Krugman]], writing for ''The New York Times'' in January 2013, noted that the IGM Forum did not focus on areas that are disputed by macroeconomists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/01/05/ideology-and-economics/ |date=January 5, 2013 |title=Ideology and Economics |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |accessdate=July 10, 2016 |author=Paul Krugman}}</ref>

The [[George Mason University]] economist [[Bryan Caplan]], writing for the economics blog [[EconLog]], said "its members seem to lean heavily [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]" and that "the IGM ought to at least explicitly disclose its panelists' political allegiances".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://econlog.econlib.org/archives/2012/07/igm_and_economi.html |author=Bryan Caplan |date=July 27, 2012 |title=IGM, Economic Consensus, and Partisan Bias |publisher=EconLog |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref>

